## 1. Project Description

**Finance Buddy** is an AI-first personal finance companion designed to teach young adults how to manage their money — from budgeting and saving to investing and credit building. Users name their own AI buddy, complete a personalized onboarding quiz, and receive a tailored financial education experience powered by the Anthropic Claude API. The app combines learning, budgeting, simulated paper trading, loan management, credit card guidance, and an always-available AI chatbot into one unified platform.

Finance Buddy is **not a trading platform** and **not a robo-advisor**. It is a **financial education engine wrapped in a companion experience** — where AI is the product, not a feature.

---

## 2. The Problem

**Financial illiteracy is one of the largest unsolved problems facing young adults today.**

Personal finance is one of the most critical life skills — yet it is almost never taught. Most primary schools, high schools, and colleges don't include personal finance in their curriculum unless a student is specifically majoring in finance or business. The result is an entire generation entering adulthood with no understanding of budgeting, saving, investing, credit, taxes, or retirement planning.

The reality for most young adults:

- **Schools don't teach it.** Only 23 states in the U.S. require any personal finance coursework in high school, and even those requirements are often minimal — a single semester at most.
- **Parents may not teach it either.** Many parents aren't financially literate themselves, or they come from backgrounds where money was never openly discussed. The cycle of financial illiteracy passes from generation to generation.
- **Self-learning is overwhelming.** A motivated young person who turns to the internet finds thousands of conflicting opinions, jargon-heavy articles, predatory "get rich quick" content, and tools built for experienced investors — not beginners. Many get overwhelmed, give up, and never learn the fundamentals.
- **Existing tools assume expertise.** Budgeting apps track numbers but never explain what they mean. Investment platforms assume fluency in financial jargon. Robo-advisors automate decisions without teaching the user anything.
- **The cost of not learning is enormous.** Young adults who don't understand compound interest, credit scores, or tax-advantaged accounts lose tens or hundreds of thousands of dollars over their lifetime compared to those who start early. The gap between "knowing" and "not knowing" personal finance translates directly into generational wealth inequality.

The result: most young people guess, avoid, or delay making financial decisions — and they pay for it for decades.

**Finance Buddy exists to close this gap.**

